            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this food scale calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Measuring by weight is the most accurate way to cook and bake.
                This food scale calculator converts between
                <strong>volume units</strong> (cups, tablespoons, teaspoons,
                milliliters) and <strong>weight units</strong> (grams, ounces)
                using ingredient-specific densities.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core formulas</p>
                <p class="text-sm mb-1"><strong>1. Volume → Weight</strong></p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  \(\text{Weight (g)} = \text{Volume (mL)} \times \text{Density
                  (g/mL)}\)
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm mt-2 mb-1">
                  <strong>2. Weight → Volume</strong>
                </p>
                <p class="text-sm">
                  \(\text{Volume (mL)} = \dfrac{\text{Weight (g)}}{\text{Density
                  (g/mL)}}\)
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600 mt-2">
                  The calculator converts cups/tbsp/tsp to milliliters using
                  standard US measures, then applies the ingredient density to
                  get grams or ounces.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Step-by-step example</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Goal:</strong> A recipe calls for
                <strong>2 cups of all-purpose flour</strong>, but you want to
                weigh it.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Select <strong>All-purpose flour</strong> as the ingredient.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Enter <strong>2</strong> as the value and choose
                  <strong>cups</strong> as the “from” unit.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Choose <strong>grams</strong> as the “to” unit and click
                  <strong>Convert</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  The calculator uses 1 cup ≈ 120 g for flour, so 2 cups ≈ 240
                  g. Put your bowl on the scale, tare it, and add flour until it
                  reads about <strong>240 g</strong>.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Why grams per cup are different for each ingredient</h3>
              <p>
                A cup is a measure of <strong>space</strong>, not weight. A cup
                of feathers weighs less than a cup of sand because the density
                is different. The same is true in the kitchen:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>1 cup water ≈ <strong>240 g</strong></li>
                <li>1 cup all-purpose flour ≈ <strong>120 g</strong></li>
                <li>1 cup granulated sugar ≈ <strong>200 g</strong></li>
                <li>1 cup butter ≈ <strong>227 g</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                That’s why generic “1 cup = 240 g” conversions are misleading.
                This calculator uses
                <strong>ingredient-specific densities</strong> to give you
                realistic values.
              </p>

              <h3>Accuracy and limitations</h3>
              <p>
                The densities used here are based on common food science and
                nutrition references and assume typical packing (e.g., spooned
                and leveled flour). Real-world values can vary due to:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>How tightly ingredients are packed into the cup</li>
                <li>Grind size (e.g., fine vs coarse salt or sugar)</li>
                <li>Moisture content and brand differences</li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For critical recipes (especially baking), always treat the
                calculator as a <strong>guide</strong> and rely on your food
                scale as the final authority.
              </p>

              <h3>Tips for using a food scale effectively</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Always tare:</strong> Put your empty bowl on the scale
                  and press <strong>Tare</strong> before adding ingredients.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Weigh directly into the bowl:</strong> Add ingredients
                  one by one, taring between each, to reduce dishes and improve
                  accuracy.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Prefer grams over ounces:</strong> Grams give finer
                  resolution and are standard in professional recipes.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stick to one system:</strong> Avoid mixing cups and
                  grams in the same recipe when possible.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

